# Continuous Deployment Docs
## Deploying Afid Core 
AFID deploys are automated through GitHub actions. 

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)
## Dev environment
The dev environment is automatically deployed to whenever a change is merged into `main` in the afid core or afid-detectors repos. 

AFID core refers to the core web application and supporting services. This includes everything except for the BentoML runners.
![Image](data:image/png;base64,)
To manually deploy changes to dev use the `afid-deploy`'s `deploy-core.yaml` workflow. https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-deploy/actions/workflows/deploy-core.yaml

For Dev, environment should be dev and both docker images should be set to latest. 

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

## App environment.
Deployments to app are triggered by creating a release in the [afid core repo](https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid/). AFID follows [semantic versioning](https://semver.org/) and we generally release from the tip of the `main` branch. Once the release is published it will start a build workflow in the core repo. It will then automitcally trigger a deploy job in the [afid-deploy repo](https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-deploy/). This is all that should be needed for a normal app deploy. 
![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

Each release should automatically sync the changes to App using GitHub actions. 
![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

You may want to manually trigger a redeployment, or rollback to a previous version. This can be done by manually triggering the ["Deploy AFID Core"](https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-deploy/actions/workflows/deploy-core.yaml) job in the afid-deploy repo. You will need to click the "Run workflow" button and fill in the following fields:
- **"Use workflow from"**: This should be set to `main` regardless of the code you're deploying. This refers to the afid-deploy branch to be used.
- **"The environment being deployed to"**: This should be set to app
- **"The docker tag of the AFID core image"**: This should be the name of the release tag to be deployed. For example: `v.1.13.1`
- **The docker tag of the AFID nextjs image**: This should be the name of the release tag to be deployed. For example: `v.1.13.1`. This should be the same as the afid core tag except in very rare circumstances.

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

## Cloud environment
Deployments to cloud must be manually triggered from the afid-deploy repo's "Deploy AFID Core" task. All cloud release should have already been deployed to app, so there is no build step needed for cloud.

From the [GitHub action's page](https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-deploy/actions/workflows/deploy-core.yaml) you will need to click the "Run workflow" button and fill in the following fields:
- **"Use workflow from"**: This should be set to `main` regardless of the code you're deploying. This refers to the afid-deploy branch to be used.
- **"The environment being deployed to"**: This should be set to oracle
- **"The docker tag of the AFID core image"**: This should be the name of the release tag to be deployed. For example: `v.1.13.1`
- **The docker tag of the AFID nextjs image**: This should be the name of the release tag to be deployed. For example: `v.1.13.1`. This should be the same as the afid core tag except in very rare circumstances.
![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

## Deploying Afid Detectors

Like AFID core, afid-detectors deploys are automated through GitHub actions. Here is a top view of the detectors deployment workflows.
![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

## Dev environment
The dev environment is automatically deployed to whenever a change is merged into the afid-detectors repo.
Deployments can also be triggered manually after re-configuring the using `helm-charts/afid-detectors/values/dev.yml` using the GitHub actions workflow in the [afid-detectors repo](https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-detectors/). You can find the workflow here: 
https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-deploy/actions/workflows/deploy-detectors.yaml
1. Click on Run workflow button
2. Select the Environment to run the deployment like dev
3. Leave the .detectors empty (when no .detectors is given it defaults to using the values/$ENVIRONMENT.yml)
4. Run workflow

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

##  App environment
Deployments to app are triggered by creating a release in the [afid-detectors repo](https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-detectors/). AFID follows [semantic versioning](https://semver.org/) and we generally release from the tip of the `main` branch. Once the release is published it will start a build workflow in the afid-detectors repo. It will then automatically trigger a deploy job in the [afid-deploy repo](https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-deploy/). This is all that should be needed for a normal app deploy. 
New releases can be created by going to this page: https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-detectors/releases/new

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

Each release will trigger a GitHub actions that will build the corresponding detector images and then deploy them to app. 

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

Finally, it is also possible to manually trigger the deployment from the afid-deploy workflow similar to dev. 
[![Image](data:image/png;base64,)](https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-deploy/actions/workflows/deploy-detectors.yaml)
##  Cloud environment
Deployments to cloud must be manually triggered, and the process is similar to that of app and dev.

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

The major difference here is that the when the environment selected is oracle, it copies the detectors values from the file `helm-charts/afid-detectors/values/app.yml` to `helm-charts/afid-detectors/values/oracle.yml`. Then the helm chart is installed with the new file values. 

The definition for all detectors currently deployed in Oracle can be found [here](https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-deploy/blob/main/helm-charts/afid-detectors/values/oracle.yaml). The detectors to be deployed to Cloud will be a subset of ones from App. This can be used to filter out only production ready models to be available in Cloud. 
To specify that a model is to be included or not in the Cloud environment, the developer can add a label `production: true | false`  to the corresponding `bentofile.yaml` while building the detector image. 

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)

This label is later used in GitHub workflow to filter out detectors while writing values to `oracle.yml` file. 
![Image](data:image/png;base64,)
Now you can kick off the deployment job by going to the ["Deploy AFID Detectors"](https://github.com/AutomatedFishID/afid-deploy/actions/workflows/deploy-detectors.yaml) Job and clicking "Run worklow". Enter the following inputs:
- **The environment being deployed to**: This should be set to oracle

After clicking "Run workflow" the deployment will begin.

![Image](data:image/png;base64,)
